This is the first time I've submitted anything, and not entirely certain this is even the correct section.  I've had Kerbal approximately a year, and the game randomly crashes.  When it crashes, I get a dialog box from Windows that says the program has stopped working correctly, and Windows will try to find a solution.  Of course Windows finds no solution.  The game does not typically generate a crash report.  The game crashes at random times, with no real rhyme or reason.  The longer a save file has existed, the more unstable it becomes.  Switching from the map view to the vessel view definitely makes the game more unstable.  Switching to the space center, and then back to a vessel makes it more unstable.  There is no set way to make the game crash 100% of the time.  It happens in all modes, (career, sandbox, science), it does not depend on type of parts, or vessel configuration.  It will typically crash though, when a condition changes, i.e., change in throttle, trigger next stage, pressing any steering button.  It is unusual that I can play the game longer than about 15 minutes without a crash.  I purchased the game from Steam, and I have 2 computers with different hardware, that has been upgraded within the last year, so technically you could say I've tried playing the game on 4 different hardware configurations.  I am running Windows 10 on both machines.  The only mod I've tried to install is Mechjeb, it is only installed locally on one of the machines, and quite frankly it doesn't seem to affect stability in any way, shape, or form.  I really enjoy this game, however; it is borderline unplayable due to the crashes.  If anyone has any ideas I'm game.  Attached below is dxdialog. ------------------

Apologies if you've already done this, but make sure you're running the 64-bit version. The 32-bit version can frequently run out of memory and cause the kind of crashes you mentioned, and if you are playing from Steam it will run 32-bit by default.

Aside from vital information that BadOaks said, make sure your machine is actually stable.

Regardless of which OS (Linux, Mac, Windows) you are running, download Prime SP2004 and run (in case of Linux/Mac via Wine) multiple instances of it for amount of CPU cores you have. Then start the CPU and memory burn test and let it run for at least 5 hours.

The best way is to use ECC-enabled memory (like unbuffered non-registered ECC typically for uni-processor and registered ECC for multi-processors systems). Granted the bit-flip happens not very often (like 2 to 0 times per month on heavy use), it does happen. Unfortunately ECC is limited to Xeon and server motherboards for Intel and only to ASUS brand boards (to my knowledge) but any processor for AMD.
